participate in trade, the North offers empty deals to "partners" that it regards as unequal. Using a mixed-methods approach, J. P. Singh exposes the actual position beneath the North's image of benevolence and empathy: either join in the type of trade that developed countries offer, or be cast aside as obstreperous and unwilling. Singh reveals how the global North ultimately bars developing nations from flourishing. His findings chart a path forward, showing that developing nations can garner favorable concessions by drawing on unique strengths and through collective advocacy. Sweet Talk offers a provocative rethinking of how far our international relations have come and how far we still have to go.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aInternational economic relations. 0aPaternalism. 4aGATT. 4aNorth-South. 4aWTO. 4acoalitions. 4ajustice. 4anegotiations. 4apaternalism. 4aracism. 4areciprocity. 4atrade. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / Trade & Tariffs.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311070369640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150360105540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503601055423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503601055.jpg  a978-3-11-070369-6  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles